(1, 1, 'Mr WordPress', '', 'http://wordpress.org/', '', '2010-06-18 20:51:35', '2010-06-18 20:51:35', 'Hi, this is a comment.<br />To delete a comment, just log in and view the post&#039;s comments. There you will have the option to edit or delete them.', 0, 'post-trashed', '', '', 0, 0),
(2, 34, 'Valerie', 'Valgodchock07@yahoo.com', '', '75.15.200.201', '2013-06-18 16:43:16', '2013-06-18 16:43:16', 'Never use Vaseline! Use extra virgin coconut oil! It''s healthy and not made of petroleum jelly! Coconut oil detoxes your body while petroleum jelly contaminates it with poisons. Coconut Oil is the very best make up remover, skin moisturizer for face and body!', 0, '1', '', '', 0, 0),
(3, 34, 'Shawna', 'wilhelmfalkdietrich@gmail.com', '', '65.60.143.119', '2013-06-18 20:04:02', '2013-06-18 20:04:02', 'You realize that Coconut oil and Petroleum jelly perform entirely different functions for skin. Of course you don''t because you''ve bought into new age hype. Vaseline doesn''t absorb into skin. It''s not oil. It works by keeping water in. There are many types of petroleum. Petroleum jelly sold for cosmetics is well-refined and has to be below a certain threshold for impurities.\n\nCoconut oil would likely be an emollient where petroleum jelly is an occlusive. They are miles away in function. \n\nIf you want to make a comparison, compare mineral oil and coconut oil as they perform the same function. Sadly though, even if you did you would still be wrong because mineral oil as used in cosmetics has no safety concerns at all.', 0, '1', '', '', 2, 0),
(4, 34, 'Valerie', 'Valgodchock07@yahoo.com', '', '70.211.66.229', '2013-06-19 18:31:23', '2013-06-19 18:31:23', 'Yes I bought into the "new age hype" because its all natural and the way the ancient people''s used to do things. \n\nI used to use both Petroleum jelly and mineral oil on my eyes. My eye doctor told me to stop using both because they build up in the eye. He said it turns yellow and he has had to scrape it out of a few patients eyes. He said it not me, 30 years ago.\n\nWe may never agree, and I can live with that. I''m Native American Indian and believe the more man touches by manufacturing and mass producing anything, the less beneficial it is. Especially the more research that is coming out now about pesticides, processed foods, etc. \n\nThe skin is the largest organ of the body. I try hard to be good to it not only by the products I use, but also with what I eat and drink. It takes 26 seconds for the body to absorb thru the skin anything applied to it  and hit the blood stream.', 0, '1', '', '', 3, 0),
(5, 34, 'Shawna', 'wilhelmfalkdietrich@gmail.com', '', '65.60.143.119', '2013-06-19 18:57:30', '2013-06-19 18:57:30', '@ Valerie (I apologize, I don;t know how to use this site quite yet but I don''t see a direct reply button to you.)\n\nAncient people used to not bathe as well. They often had lice and didn''t clean their hair. Ancient people suffered from a variety of skin ailments that would make you vomit on sight. Ancient people had more important things to worry about than rubbing coconut oil into their skin. Stuff like getting food and not having diarrhea. \n\nAncient people, by and large, did not lead great lives. Anyone that believes otherwise isn''t worth my time, seriously. I don''t mind people having differing opinions so long as they are based in fact. \n\nBeing Native American Indian means absolutely nothing in regards to what you know about biology, chemistry, the natural world or history. I know Indians and most of them have bigger problems than rubbing coconut oil (which they wouldn''t even have had in ''ancient times'') into their skin. Stuff like rampant poverty on reservations. Alcohol and drug abuse. Lack of work and lack of access to medical care. What I mean is, your lineage isn''t important at all to this conversation. At all. It gives you no validity in regards to what you are saying.\n\nWe are all here because we want to take care of our skin and look nice. New age hype that doesn''t match with science or history is not good information and it only serves to confuse people. The fact that you recommended using an emollient because a specific occlusive is ''bad for you'' shows you don''t know the differences between these products. \n\nPetroleum Jelly is a minimally processed product. It used to accumulate naturally on oil rigs where it was discovered (oil by the way is a natural product of the earth). Now it is made in a more controlled manner like ALL things are. Really the only thing someone can say about Petroleum Jelly is that it shouldn''t be inhaled, because of the risk of lipid pneumonia. But any oil will cause lipid pneumonia if inhaled because that is the catalyst for that disease.', 0, '1', '', '', 3, 0),
