(3141, 1, '2013-10-27 12:56:36', '2013-10-27 12:56:36', '<span style="font-size:medium;">I’m a bit of a germ phone, I have to admit. I sanitize (or wash) my hands after touching just about everything: door handles, elevator buttons (you wouldn’t believe how many germs exist on these!), money, other people’s hands…you name it. I also never, ever, ever wear bare feet in a locker or yoga room; I always have a pair of flip flops handy—and if I forget (as I did this morning), I wear socks…even in the gym shower.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-size:medium;">I mean, really, I have good reason to do so: there are germs everywhere and if I can prevent myself from touching them, I’m less likely to get sick (or so I think) or worse yet, get some icky fungal infection or warts.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-size:medium;">But—like so many other people—I rarely wash my makeup brushes. Beyond gross, yes, I 100% agree. My reasons for not doing so are valid (or so I tell myself): I’m busy—and I don’t use all my makeup brushes (I have many) all the time. I usually brush on a bit of blush (or powder) and go. Or I just swipe on some eye shadow here and there—with a shadow brush—when I need to add a bit of color. I mean how dirty can they really get? </span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-size:medium;">Turns out…plenty.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-size:medium;">Makeup brushes are filled with dust, dead skin cells, dirt—and bacteria. Oil from our skin, plus makeup left on brushes, creates an environment that’s the perfect breeding ground for bacteria. Leave all that on there for days, weeks, and months…and you won’t want to see what you’re layering on your skin.</span>\r\n\r\nThe worst that can happen? On the very surface, these bacteria can contribute to breakouts and skin rashes. But, when it comes to anything near the eyes, you can also develop bacterial conjunctivitis (aka pink eye). Not pretty.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-size:medium;">How to stop this cycle: you’ve got to wash your makeup brushes once a week or once every two weeks at the very least. The easiest way to do it: take your brush immediately after using it (otherwise, you’ll forget), dab with a tiny bit of baby shampoo (that way, it won’t irritate your eyes or your skin), suds it up with warm water, rinse, and lay flat to dry. (After all, you wash your skin at least once a day…why not your makeup brushes?)</span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-size:medium;">There are alcohol-based spray-on products that help disinfect your brushes; they’re easy to use but—and I’ve tried these—but the truth is you still need to rinse your brushes under warm water (and even some shampoo) to get rid of the residual makeup left over on the brush. \r\n\r\n<span style="font-size:medium;">After looking at bacteria growing in petri dishes (and on makeup brushes), I’ve become a convert. Not only did I give my makeup drawer a fall cleaning to narrow my brushes down to the ones that are essential (it simplifies my cleaning). I also gave them (plus my hair brushes, too) all a good washing—and plan to do so regularly. Because the alternative is, well, just plain disgusting!</span>\r\n\r\n', 'The Not-So-Pretty Reality of Your Makeup Bag', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '3129-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-10-27 12:56:36', '2013-10-27 12:56:36', '', 3129, 'http://www.preenmeblog.bitnamiapp.com//uncategorized/3129-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
